article.headline: Frosh Hardrick scores career-high 25
article.linkText: No. 16 Georgia edges No. 13 LSU in SEC clash
article.story:
ATHENS, Ga. (AP) -- Janese Hardrick is a freshman, which means
"she doesn't know where she parked her car this morning,"
according to Georgia coach Andy Landers

But Hardrick knew when to kick her game into high gear,
dominating the end of the half and the end of the game, sparking
Georgia (No. 16 ESPN/USA Today, No. 17 AP) to an 80-74 win over LSU (No. 13 ESPN/USA Today, No. 12 AP) Sunday.

Hardrick scored a career-high 25 points, ending Georgia's
three-game losing streak and LSU's 15-game winning streak.

"Janese kept coming up big time after time," Landers said.
"She made a lot of plays on both ends of the floor."

Hardrick scored the last six points of the first half, boosting
the Lady Dogs to a 34-30 lead. Then as the game ended, Hardrick
scored six of Georgia's final 10 points.

"We did not figure her in for 25 points," said LSU associate
head coach Pokey Chatman. "I think we did a good job taking away
some of their weapons, but they had a player step up. I can't take
anything away from her."

LSU's head coach Sue Gunter was on the bench for her 1,000th
NCAA game but was still weak after recovering from a viral
infection and bronchitis, and Chatman directed the game.

Christi Thomas added 20 points for the Lady Dogs (14-5, 3-3
Southeastern Conference) and Alexis Kendrick 15. LSU (16-3, 4-1
SEC) got 24 points from Seimone Augustus and 22 from Doneeka
Hodges.

Hardrick, starting for just the second time this season, hit a 3
from two steps behind the arc with 1:13 to play to put Georgia
ahead 73-70, but LSU's Augustus hit just her seventh 3 of the
season with 56.8 seconds to play to tie the game.

Two free throws by Thomas with 39.7 to play put Georgia ahead
for good, 75-73. Augustus missed a short jumper, and LSU's Crystal
White lost the offensive rebound out of bounds. The Lady Tigers
fouled Hardrick, a 77 percent free-throw shooter, and she made two
with 20.2 seconds to play.

Thomas fouled out on LSU's next possession, but Temeka Johnson,
an 81-percent free-throw shooter, could hit only one of two with
16.3 to play. One more free throw by Hardrick and two by Sherill
Baker accounted for the final score.

Georgia played without 6-foot-6 forward Kara Braxton, sidelined
before the game with a stomach virus. She averages 14.4 points and
8.4 rebounds a game.

"I think that made the team focus," said Landers. "I have
never been a part of a team that didn't play better than it was
expected to after something like that happens.

"I thought we had a lot of kids step up and make plays," he
added. "It was such a team win."

Mired in a three-game losing streak, the longest ever in
Landers' 25 years at Georgia, the Lady Dogs fell behind early,
20-11 midway through the first half after two free throws by
Augustus. But Georgia scored 10 straight points, capped by a layup
by Hardrick with 6:57 to go in the half to take its first lead at
23-22.

Hardrick scored four points in the last 10 seconds of the first
half. She intercepted a pass for a breakaway layup, and LSU stepped
on the line in its haste to in-bound the ball, setting up Hardrick
for two free throws with 2.3 seconds to go in the half.

LSU failed to score a field goal for the first five minutes of
the second half, by which time Georgia led 44-32 after Jessica
Pierce's jumper from the corner. Hardrick gave Georgia a 13-point
lead at 11:17 with another breakaway layup.

But Hodges caught fire for the Lady Tigers, hitting a pair of 3s
to start a 12-0 run. LSU tied the game twice in the final four
minutes, but could never get the lead.

LSU out-rebounded Georgia 47-36, including 21 offensive
rebounds, but could not capitalize because of a poor shooting,
hitting just 32 percent from the field.

The game was Landers' 599th win as the head coach at Georgia.
